Additional_Comments: The location of the bus stop is unsafe for pedestrians due to the lack of crosswalk in the area. Vehicles are constantly speeding and using bike lanes as driving lanes in the mornings, making it a game to get to the bus stop (if crossing Peters St). The bus stop is also a temporary location as the previous location a few yards away had been blocked due to construction. Please help us in Castleberry Hill make this a more safe place!!

Obstacle_Desc: Blocked by parked cars
Additional_Comments:
Constant speeding traffic due to the intersection being at the bottom of a hill and nothing to stop or slow cars, buses, delivery trucks, etc.

Currently there is only a stop sign at Haynes St SW and no traffic calming/red light/stop sign on Peters St SW. There is a stop light at the top of the hill at Peters St / Fair, but it is often green, so cars are already speeding by the time they come down the hill. This creates a dangerous impediment for residents trying to cross Peters St SW since there is NO crosswalk either.

Bike lanes on Peters St SW were made so wide with the re-striping a few years ago that most vehicles assume it’s a secondary lane, creating unsafe areas for bicycles (and pedestrians forced to stand along those lanes). Every day I witness cars going into the bike lane to get around cars that are waiting to turn onto Haynes St SW.

During construction of new apartments right there, the MARTA bus stop and sidewalk at that area were completely blocked forcing pedestrians to stand in the road to catch the bus. I was able to submit requests to ATL311 to have a temporary bus stop moved a few yards north to an unblocked area.

The main issues is there is NO crosswalk for pedestrians to cross Peters St SW to get to the bus stop at this intersection, forcing us to dart in between cars each morning. This is going to become even worse once all of the new offices and apartments open this year in the area. I have sent messages to Councilwoman Cleta Winslow as well as State Rep. Pat Gardner--but I've yet to hear any response. I've also included in those messages numerous photos that I've taken to prove all of the above points, all in an effort to bring this dangerous intersection to light and try to create a safer area for pedestrians and cyclists.

Very dangerous to cross from west to east across Glen Iris here. I nearly get hit every single day in the afternoons. Cars headed southbound sometimes pay attention although they’ll blow by me, however those headed northbound crest over a hill and then accelerate downhill with little to no regard to my life or those I ride with. I am a confident urbanist, healthy, and 30. I fear for any child who has interest in crossing this street. Children do cross this street headed to the pond, playground, BeltLine, and now the grocery store. We need to make it safer, preferably with a stop sign.

While the street is well lit, the one light that doesn’t work is the light the bus stop is attached to. Motorists travel dangerously fast here and crossing the street is an arduous task. I see runners and people walking their dog be ignored crossing the street often by motorists. When I come the opposite direction on this route and attempt to cross the street from west to East I nearly get hit every single time I cross the road. There’s a crest on a hill just south of here that blocks drivers views of the crosswalks and pedestrians, then drivers pick up speed going downhill. Despite sidewalks, it does not feel safe walking between this stop and North Ave due to occasional high speeds barreling through.

A street light needs to be placed at bus stop, especially in the fall winter when it gets dark early and people are going home from work. There really isn’t room for a bench, side walk is roughly 8’ wide. A canopy can be possibly anchored to the retaining wall to provide shade in the summer and shelter during the rain. It would be nice to see electronic boards at bigger stops to show an eta when the next bus is coming. Chicago I know has some at their bus stops.
